Reasoning: The claim is supported by evidence from paper ID 1287809, "Cost-effectiveness of 10-Year Risk Thresholds for Initiation of Statin Therapy for Primary Prevention of Cardiovascular Disease." This paper directly compares the cost-effectiveness of the 7.5% and 10% ASCVD risk thresholds for initiating statin therapy. The study found that the 7.5% or higher ASCVD threshold had an incremental cost-effectiveness ratio (ICER) of $37,000/QALY compared with a 10% or higher threshold (Proposition ID: prop_753, Chunk ID: chunk_17270). An ICER of $37,000/QALY indicates that for every additional quality-adjusted life-year gained by using the 7.5% threshold, there is an additional cost of $37,000 compared to the 10% threshold. This implies that the 7.5% threshold is less cost-effective than the 10% threshold, as it incurs a higher cost per QALY gained. The paper concludes that while the 7.5% threshold has an "acceptable cost-effectiveness profile," more lenient thresholds (e.g., 4.0% or 3.0%) would be "optimal" at higher cost-effectiveness thresholds, further suggesting that the 7.5% threshold is not the most cost-effective option when compared to a higher threshold like 10%.
